UP|40|PF|Y|nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| This was an interesting hand, and a good example of competitive bidding judgement. On these types of hands, unfortunately, there are no hard and fast rules, but I will explain why I think everyone made good bids.  2 diamonds was fine. Some experts would argue moe has too much outside strength, but you know that I feel you should open a weak 2 any time you have a six card suit and 5-10 HCP. 4@S was fine as well, it puts me under a lot of pressure, and kia could easily be making 4@S  if aggie has the right hand. |
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| Now, I have a problem.  It looks to me likely that they will make 4@S because I have so many diamonds. It is likely kia has at most one diamond, and maybe none. We have a 10 card fit, so that only leaves 3 for the opponents.  Now, by my competitive guidelines, since we have a 10 card fit, 4@D should be fine, but 5 may be a bit too high.  And this is one of the few instances where vulnerability must be taken into account. |
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| A non-vul game is worth 420 (in spades) a vul game is worth 620.  Doubled undertricks non-vul are down 1=100, then 300 for down 2, 500 for down 3, and 800 for down 4. On the other hand,  doubled undertricks vulnerable are 200, 500, 800, 1100.  So what does that all mean?  It means if you are thinking about a sacrifice, at equal vulnerability you come out ahead if you go down 2, and slightly behind if down 3. Therefore,  you should consider a sacrifice bid at equal vulnerability if you are pretty sure you are down 2 or less, and not worry too much if you are down 3 -imps only.|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| If you are not vul, and the opponents are vul, then you can afford to be down 3.  However, if you are vul and the opponents are not, then you can only afford to be down 1. For those considerations, it was likely we were only down 1 or 2, and decided at equal vul to bid 5.  It is more judgement than anything else. You have to decide if you think the opps are making, and how much you will go down.  It might have worked out badly (for example, suppose moe did not have the ace of clubs.)  Also, by bidding 5@D I put pressure on aggie, and she might guess wrong|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| BTW, just to not keep you in suspense, aggie, you make 5@S. You pitch a heart on the Ace of diamonds.  Actually, she wanted to bid 5@S, which turns out to make, but I told her not to. And here is my reasoning. When deciding whether to defend or declare, you have to look at where your points are located and whether or not they fit well with partner.  In this case, aggie has diamond points. since kia is likely to be void in diamonds, they don't fit well with kia. Granted, he might be able to throw away a loser, as he can, but they don't fit well. |
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| In addition, aggie has a singleton spade, so if kia has the ace of spades, which is quite likely, she will get a ruff. So she can just about guarantee we will be down 2 in that case, ace of spades, spade ruff, and two red aces  and we might be down more.  So, if I had aggie's hand I would double.  As I said, it turns out 5@S is slightly better (by 120 points), but if she is down in 5 spades, then she turns a big gain into a loss.  On average, I think double by aggie is better. Again, these hands require judgement and experience, but I am trying to show you how experts analyze these hands when making their decisions.|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| Basically if you are short in partner's suit, and have points in the opponents suit, that tends to want to make you defend.  Conversely if you have points and/or length in partner's suit, you want to declare. |
