|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| Well, this was a pretty straight forward hand for a change :). However, let me just go over Bergen Raises for those who are not totally familiar with it. Marty Bergen is a big believer in preempting the opponents when you have a good fit. Bergen felt that rather than making the auction 1@S-3@S or 1@H-3@H showing responder has a limit raise (4 card support and 9-11 pts), he wanted it to show a weak hand with 4 card support.  The idea being it was likely the opponents had a fit, and he wanted to make it difficult for them to find their fit.|
PG| ***** 89 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| You will note this is in line with my competitive guidelines, where I said it is ok to compete to the 3 level with a 9 card fit. Anyhow,  he decided 3@S should show a weak hand and as 3@C and 3@D as weak jump shifts were not that useful he decided to use them to show stronger hands with 4 card support. Originally, he said 3@C shows 4 card support with a good 6 to a bad 9, and 3@D shows a limit raise. However, most people have since reversed the meaning of those bids, as I did here, so 3@D is weaker than 3@C. |
PG| ***** 90 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2
|cp|8|at|^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| The reason I prefer what is known as "Reverse Bergen" is, it is more likely you want to explore for game when pard has the stronger hand and 3@C leaves more bidding room. I play Bergen even by a passed hand. Several kibs asked me that question. I see no reason not to still play Bergen if you are a passed hand. |
